We recently encountered this. You _can_ get the mapping programmatically from the JIRA client and we ended up building the below utility class to handle this.

On second though, it makes better sense to include this directly in the library in some better way, but in the meantime, I'll share our working solution:

```
class CustomFields(object):
    """
    Allows you to map a custom field name to it's internal ID.
    e.g. My Custom Field -> customfield_10414
    """
    def __init__(self, jira_client):
        self.field_name_to_id = {}
        self.field_id_to_name = {}
        for field in jira_client.fields():
            name, id = field['name'], field['id']
            self.field_name_to_id[name] = id
            self.field_id_to_name[id] = name

    def id(self, field_name):
        try:
            return self.field_name_to_id[field_name]
        except KeyError, e:
            raise KeyError("Unknown custom field name: '%s'\n"
                           "Known field names are: %s" % (str(e), self.field_name_to_id.keys()))

    def name(self, field_id):
        try:
            return self.field_id_to_name[field_id]
        except KeyError, e:
            raise KeyError("Unknown custom field id: '%s'\n"
                           "Known field ids are: %s" % (str(e), self.field_id_to_name.keys()))
```

